    "about": "The Indian Institute of Technology Bhubaneswar (IIT Bhubaneswar) was established on 22 July 2008, following decades of demand for an IIT in Odisha due to perceived neglect by the central government, leading to protests and political agitation. The announcement was made by then-Prime Minister Manmohan Singh on 15 August 2007, during India's 60th Independence anniversary, and approved in the 54th National Development Council meeting in December 2007 as part of the 11th Five-Year Plan. The Union Cabinet approved setting up eight new IITs, including IIT Bhubaneswar, at a cost of ₹760 crore per institute, with IIT Kharagpur mentoring it initially. The institute started operations on 23 July 2008 with 95 students at IIT Kharagpur, shifting to Bhubaneswar in 2009, and became an Institute of National Importance on 29 June 2012. The permanent campus at Kansapada, spanning 936 acres, was inaugurated by Prime Minister Narendra Modi on 24 December 2018, with construction beginning in 2011 and operations starting from the 2015-16 academic year. The campus, near Jatni and 24 km from Bhubaneswar, features a science park for industry-oriented research and is part of an emerging education hub with nearby institutions like AIIMS Bhubaneswar and NISER. IIT Bhubaneswar also established a marine campus near Chilka Lake in 2011 for research in marine sciences.\n\nThe institute is governed under a structure with the President of India at the top, followed by the IIT Council, board of governors, director, and deans. The institute offers BTech (Hons.) in disciplines like Computer Science, Civil, Electrical, Electronics and Communication, Mechanical, and Metallurgical and Materials Engineering, with dual degree courses in Mechanical and Civil. Admissions are through JEE Advanced for undergraduates and GATE for postgraduates, with a total undergraduate intake of 260 students as of 2016, aiming for 10,000 students in 15 years. It also offers MTech, joint MTech-PhD, and PhD programs, following a credit-based system with spring, autumn, and summer quarters. The institute adopts an interdisciplinary approach with Schools instead of departments, covering areas like Basic Sciences, Engineering, and Humanities.\n\nThe campus, located in a rural setting, is well-connected with Khurda Rd railway station 4 km away and Biju Patnaik Airport 35 km away. Facilities include a central library with 23,000 textbooks and access to IIT Kharagpur’s online resources. Student life is vibrant with festivals like Alma Fiesta (socio-cultural) and Wissenaire (techno-management), a sports festival Aarohan, and events like SPIC MACAY for Indian classical arts. The institute introduced Odissi dance as a BTech subject in 2015, a first among IITs. It also supports entrepreneurship through a Startup Centre and Research and Entrepreneurship Park, established with government funding.\n\nRankings include 701–750 globally by QS World University Rankings 2022, 36th in India for engineering by NIRF 2022, and 11th by India Today 2022. The institute has 2,912 students and 204 faculty, with a student-faculty ratio of approximately 14:1, and a campus area of 936 acres.",
