    "about": "Indian Institute of Technology Tirupati (IIT Tirupati), established in 2015, is a third-generation IIT located in Yerpedu, Tirupati District, Andhra Pradesh, initially mentored by IIT Madras. The institute began operations on August 5, 2015, at a temporary campus in Chadalawada Nagar, with the permanent campus foundation stone laid by Union Minister Smriti Irani, former Vice President M. Venkaiah Naidu, and Chief Minister N. Chandrababu Naidu. The permanent campus, spanning 540 acres, is under development in multiple stages, with the North Campus (Stage 1C) completed by December 2023, shifting all operations there from January 2024. The campus includes academic zones with department buildings, laboratories, a Central Instrumentation Facility, lecture hall complex, and administrative building, alongside hostel zones with 1,000 rooms, a central dining facility, and sports facilities. Residential zones feature 168 apartments, a 20-room guest house, and the Director's bungalow, with two 10-acre lakes for rainwater harvesting. The construction has received awards like the GRIHA Council Award and RoSPA Gold Award for sustainable practices.\n\nAcademically, IIT Tirupati offers 4-year B.Tech, 2-year M.Sc, M.S., M.Tech (started in 2018), Master of Public Policy, and Ph.D. programs across engineering, science, and humanities, with admissions through IIT-JEE-Advanced for B.Tech and GATE/JAM for postgraduate programs. It started with 106 students in four B.Tech programs in 2015, expanding to include Chemical Engineering in 2018 and various master's programs by 2020, with current enrollment at 1,168 students, including 852 undergraduates, 167 postgraduates, and 149 Ph.D. students. The institute has a 21.87% female enrollment in B.Tech and 20.5% overall, offering scholarships for economically marginal groups and sponsoring nine Indian Army officers for M.Tech in 2020. It plans to start a School of Design and Materials Science department, aiming to accommodate 12,000 students by 2040.\n\nStudent life is vibrant, with the annual cultural festival Tirutsava in February featuring technical and cultural events, and active SPIC MACAY and 14 clubs like Techmaniacs and Xcite, promoting extracurricular activities and mental well-being through Sarathi. Sports facilities include volleyball and basketball courts, and a fitness club under the Fit India Movement. The institute ranks 61st in NIRF 2024 for engineering. International collaborations include MoUs with Dalhousie University, Shastri Indo-Canadian Institute, Mitacs, and the Indo-European Heritage network, with a joint CAMOST center with IISER Tirupati for research in atomic, molecular, and optical sciences.",
